        {
            "id": "6576b617d8a94470b69d3",
            "questionText": "A refrigerator operates in a room with a temperature of $!$27^{\\circ}C$!$, while maintaining its interior at $!$5^{\\circ}C$!$. During a 24-hour period, the refrigerator must remove $!$8.64 \\times 10^6 J$!$ of heat from its interior in order to keep its contents at the desired temperature. Assuming the refrigerator operates as an ideal Carnot cycle working in reverse, calculate the amount of electrical energy (work) in Joules that must be supplied to the refrigerator during this period.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "0440f3496a5d4d6a82ef7",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by converting the given temperatures from Celsius to Kelvin. Identify the correct conversion relation to change a temperature expressed in \u00b0C to Kelvin.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T(K)=T(\u00b0C)+273$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T(K)=T(\u00b0C)-273$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T(K)=T(\u00b0C)+100$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "5f5fc98012d94b99a0267",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the Kelvin values obtained, we need to determine the coefficient of performance (COP) or efficiency for a reversed Carnot cycle. Please select the correct expression that represents the COP in terms of the cold and hot reservoir temperatures.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "eb2ed1a7-e528-4b88-8bd6-db3a653c73cf"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$COP=\\frac{T_c}{T_h-T_c}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$COP=\\frac{T_h-T_c}{T_c}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$COP=\\frac{T_h}{T_h-T_c}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "6518faab253c4b99b1cff",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have the COP and the amount of heat removed, what formula describes the relationship between the extracted heat and the COP?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$COP = \\frac{\\text{heat removed}}{\\text{work done}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$COP = \\frac{\\text{work done}}{\\text{heat removed}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "6518faab253c4b99bdfaf",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the formula from the previous step, calculate the work done by the refrigerator.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
